The pattern across all 10 deprivation deciles reveals {% if ratio > 3 %}a steep gradient, with service dropping sharply as deprivation rises — consistent with market failure in commercially unattractive corridors{% else %}a moderate gradient, suggesting partial but incomplete equalisation through contracted service subsidies{% endif %}.

## Policy Implications

This decile analysis provides direct evidence for targeting transport investment. Under the DfT's Bus Back Better strategy and the Bus Services Act 2025, LTAs are expected to demonstrate how Enhanced Partnership Plans or franchising schemes will address service gaps in deprived areas. A disparity ratio above {{ ratio|round(1) }} would typically justify prioritising new or enhanced routes in the bottom 3–4 deprivation deciles.

Where LTAs apply for Bus Service Improvement Plan (BSIP) funding, this disparity evidence can strengthen the case for subsidy to commercially marginal but socially necessary routes.

*Methodology: LSOAs ranked by IMD 2025 composite score, divided into 10 equal-population deciles. Service measure is {{ unit }} per LSOA, averaged within each decile. Census 2021 population denominators applied throughout.*
